  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3252516623" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3252516623" />
    <a title="Z. F." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22548315-z-f"><img alt="Z. F." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1625681145p2/22548315.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3252516623?book_show_action=true">Apr 28, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Z. F." class="user" itemprop="url" name="Z. F." href="/user/show/22548315-z-f">Z. F.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780199536047" href="/book/show/2924651-fathers-and-sons">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22548315-z-f?shelf=translated">translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22548315-z-f?shelf=what-is-love">what-is-love</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22548315-z-f?shelf=god-and-vodka">god-and-vodka</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22548315-z-f?shelf=family-matters">family-matters</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22548315-z-f?shelf=1850-to-1899">1850-to-1899</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3252516623" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15157743363801265867"><b>
  <i>&quot;Every single man hangs by a thread, a bottomless pit can open beneath him any minute, and yet he still goes on thinking up unpleasantness for himself and making a mess of his life.&quot;</i>
</b><br/><br/>I don&apos;t know why <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/22548315?shelf=god-and-vodka' rel='nofollow noopener'>these old Russian novels</a> are such catnip for me. It&apos;s always the same dreary stuff, a bunch of landed aristocrats with ten names apiece discussing European intellectual trends and the nature of the soul while the serfs break their backs in the fields. Everyone&apos;s shabby and penniless and having af</span>
  <span id="freeText15157743363801265867" style="display:none"><b>
  <i>"Every single man hangs by a thread, a bottomless pit can open beneath him any minute, and yet he still goes on thinking up unpleasantness for himself and making a mess of his life."</i>
</b><br /><br />I don't know why <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/22548315?shelf=god-and-vodka" rel="nofollow noopener">these old Russian novels</a> are such catnip for me. It's always the same dreary stuff, a bunch of landed aristocrats with ten names apiece discussing European intellectual trends and the nature of the soul while the serfs break their backs in the fields. Everyone's shabby and penniless and having affairs, there's usually some young hothead fresh from the university causing trouble with his New Ideas, and by the end at least one of them is dead—but I can't get enough of it.<br /><br />Ivan Turgenev's <i>Fathers and Sons</i>, published in 1862, is credited as one of the first "modern" novels in Russian. That means it also serves as a sort of blueprint for a lot of the stuff that would start appearing very shortly thereafter: your Dostoevskys and Tolstoys and the like, basically the whole genre of Russian realist fiction. You can definitely see the raw elements here that those guys would absorb into their own, by now much more iconic, novels: Tolstoy's class consciousness and all-seeing narrators, Dostoevsky's zest for pitting generations and schools of thought against one another, the mismatched romantic pairings neither of them could resist. (To say nothing of the Noun &amp; Noun titles: <i>Fathers and Sons</i>, <i>Crime and Punishment</i>, <i>War and Peace</i>...) On the other hand, both F.D. and L.T. apparently hated Turgenev's guts: Dostoevsky wrote him into <i>The Devils</i> as a trend-chasing sellout, and Tolstoy actually challenged him to a duel before thinking better of it. Well, that's writers for you.<br /><br />So <i>Fathers and Sons</i> is definitely interesting as a historical artifact, a sort of literary missing link. But does it actually make for a good read?<br /><br />Ehh, yes and no. The elevator pitch for <i>Fathers and Sons</i> is that it's about a clash between fathers and sons, i.e. the old guard vs. the new. We've got a twenty-something guy named Arkady who's just finished school in St. Petersburg and plans to spend the summer with his widowed dad on his country estate. Along with Arkady comes Bazarov: Arkady's tutor, several years his senior, who dabbles in medicine but is more concerned with living and preaching a new ideology he calls nihilism (a term Turgenev's book helped popularize). Those are the Sons. On the Fathers side we've got Arkady's easygoing liberal landowner of a dad, Nikolai, who has a live-in mistress and an illegitimate baby boy and makes clueless but well-intended gestures towards equality for his serfs, as well as Nikolai's bachelor brother Pavel, a proud aristocrat and fading playboy who immediately takes against Bazarov's irreverence and iconoclasm. That's the core conflict. Pretty straightforward setup, right?<br /><br />Of course not! This is a Russian novel. Almost as soon as Arkady and Bazarov get settled in at the estate and start causing trouble, they're off again on a series of social calls which become the whole middle section of the book. They stay for a couple weeks with a pair of aristocratic sisters and proceed to fall in love with both of them—not one apiece, I mean both boys fall in love with both women. When that situation becomes too fraught they drop in on Bazarov's parents, poor-ish country folk who dote on their son despite his snark and radicalism but whose smothering affection quickly drives him away. Then it's back to Arkady's family farm once more, where Bazarov wastes no time getting embroiled in a duel with uncle Pavel. There's more plot after that, too, but that would be spoilers.<br /><br />I'm not usually a summarizer, but it's important to impress upon you just how much Event is packed into these 200 pages. And yet somehow—even for someone like me who's usually into this stuff—the end result is surprisingly boring. Lots of things happen in, say, <i>
  <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/780576800" rel="nofollow noopener">Anna Karenina</a>
</i>, but the power of that novel lies in Tolstoy's ability to make the mundane parts in between the action just as compelling as the action itself. <i>Fathers and Sons</i> is the other way around: I found myself <i>wanting</i> more quiet moments, more introspection, but what I got was a numbing whirl of setpieces and cast changes without time to get really invested in any of it. The dynamics and conflicts I was most excited to dig into were dispensed with in a frustratingly off-handed way, while new ones kept emerging seemingly from nowhere. Structurally and symbolically it's all very well-conceived, but in execution it feels way lighter than it should. When has a Russian novel ever felt too <i>light</i>??<br /><br />But lest I come off harsher than I mean to, "boring" is not always synonymous with "bad," particularly when it comes to the classics. Whatever else it may be, <i>Fathers and Sons</i> is definitely not <i>bad</i>. It's almost always interesting to read about the social trends of another time and place, and Turgenev is all about capturing the specific, important moment he knew he was living through: when landed nobility and proto-socialists, Orthodox Christians and avowed nihilists could all share the Russian stage and look nervously towards an uncertain, probably explosive future. Guys like Dostoevsky saw all this too and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2454786958" rel="nofollow noopener">hated it</a>—young radicals always come in for a beating in his books, mainly because he was once one himself—but Turgenev is amazingly unbiased, able to convey his characters' perspectives truthfully without making any of them out to be better or worse than they are. You don't really <i>agree</i> with anyone in here, most of them you don't even like that much, but they all ring true as distinctive and multifaceted human characters.<br /><br />And because the characterization is so good, there are some individual scenes with tremendous emotional heft. Bazarov and Odintsova's tortuous non-romance, the duel, <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Bazarov's unexpected death <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>—these are all brilliantly and sensitively handled, and they go a long way towards compensating for the book's other failings. Turgenev is particularly skilled with parent-child relationships (reasonably enough) and the romantic stuff: Bazarov's parents always broke my heart, while one scene between him and Odintsova is shockingly steamy for a book this old and Russian. Bazarov is just a magnetic character in general, a sort of Russian <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2160139124" rel="nofollow noopener">Hamlet</a> with all his moods and riddles (supposedly the similarity was deliberate), and even when he's being an asshole—as he frequently is—you can't help being intrigued by what he'll do next.<br /><br />On a more technical note: I read the Richard Freeborn translation, which I don't think is a very good one. I suspect there's a degree of clunkiness to Turgenev's prose to begin with, but Freeborn certainly doesn't do him any favors, particularly with his dialogue: usually more or less in keeping with the period, sometimes pointedly modern ("they don't care a shit about it"), occasionally both too modern <i>and</i> too old-fashioned to be anything but distracting ("All right, calm down, chum. I've told you—she's the tops.") I didn't catch on till I read Freeborn's introduction (after I'd finished the book itself) that he was trying to render Bazarov's dialogue in a laconic "American" dialect, while everyone else is supposed to be more or less English, right down to the cockney serfs and servants. It's a clever idea, it would maybe work on stage or in a movie, but on the page it falls flat. If there's a Pevear and Volokhonsky version of this one out there you should probably just go with that.<br /><br />An imperfect novel, to be sure, but I'm happy to have read it. Helpful to be reminded that this sort of generational back-and-forth didn't begin this century, at least.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15157743363801265867" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


